Before it could be stopped, I hid.

A small house in the middle of nowhere. Windows that kept the world in sight and the illness at shore.

There's a kind of arithmetic you do when the rules are written for cities and you have stopped living in one. Beds stacked in hallways and living rooms. Bodies per square mile. Percent full. The ratio of what you can pay to what is on offer. I never said it out loud because in any sentence it sounds ghostly. 

It isn't. It's a ledger.

I'm not going to say where I went. There was a market with mangos and my stolen wallet. There were small businesses with kosher food, and bags of granola made by a woman across the street.

People wanted a clean answer. Stay or leave. Right or wrong. There were hashtags. The discourse, as we called it, was a shallow body of water fed by fear and hatred.

The actual question was boring: who could afford to be careful, and where, and at whose expense. It is callous. I didn't pretend to solve it. I made a calculation. The variables were:

- twenty-eight thousand bodies per square mile, where I lived; closer to two hundred, where I went
- an ICU system at eighty-five percent the day I packed, climbing
- a clinic I could walk to, with a doctor who would see me for the money I had, beds that weren't full of people who needed them more
- an economy whose premise had been suspended by the world's condition, and a woman across the street still selling granola
- a rule, written elsewhere, that I was not exactly breaking and not exactly honoring
- a year of my own life, which it turned out I was not willing to spend in a living room

The math came back with me. Some of it I have arranged into a defense — neither right nor wrong, neither life nor death, but living in the archives of other people's memories. It's not for me to say which is which.
